headline: Banks kick off earnings, Fed Chair Powell speaks: What to Watch
summary: Market Domination Overtime host Josh Lipton takes a look at the top stories for investors to watch on Tuesday, Oct. 14. Earnings season kicks off, with JPMorgan Chase (JPM), Wells Fargo (WFC), Goldman Sachs (GS), Citi (C), BlackRock (BLK), and Johnson & Johnson (JNJ) all reporting results. Federal Reserve commentary is expected from Fed Chair Jerome Powell, Fed Vice Chair for Supervision Michelle Bowman, Fed Governor Christopher Waller, and Boston Fed President Susan Collins. The Small Business Association's (SBA's) National Federation of Independent Business (NFIB) September Small Business Optimism Index will be published in the morning. Economists are expecting a slight decrease from the prior month. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination Overtime.

headline: Goldman chief delivers warning to Reeves over bank tax hikes
summary: The boss of Goldman Sachs has urged Rachel Reeves not to increase the financial burden on the banking sector amid industry concerns that it will be targeted for steep tax hikes in next month's budget.  Sky News has learnt that David Solomon delivered the warning in a private meeting with the chancellor last week, when he is said to have told her that hitting banks with higher taxes would be damaging to Britain's wider economic growth prospects.

headline: Goldman Sees US Consumers Paying More Than Half of Trump Tariffs
summary: US consumers will likely shoulder 55% of tariff costs by the end of the year, with American companies taking on 22%, the Goldman analysts wrote in an Oct. 12 research note to clients.  Foreign exporters would absorb 18% of tariff costs by cutting prices for goods, while 5% would be evaded, they wrote.  For now “US businesses are likely bearing a larger share of the costs” as it takes time to raise prices, economists Elsie Peng and David Mericle wrote in the note.
